  "local_port": 51144,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How does GST Bill will work?",
  "response": "The **Goods and Services Tax (GST)** is a comprehensive indirect tax levied on the supply of goods and services across India. The GST Bill, officially known as the **Constitution (One Hundred and Twenty-Second Amendment) Bill, 2014**, was passed by the Indian Parliament and ratified by the states. It paved the way for the implementation of GST in India, which came into effect on **1st July 2017**.\n\nHere\u2019s how GST works:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Unified Tax System**\n   - GST replaced multiple indirect taxes (like VAT, excise duty, service tax, etc.) with a single tax system.\n   - It eliminated the cascading effect of taxes (tax on tax) by allowing input tax credit (ITC) at every stage of the supply chain.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Dual GST Structure**\n   GST in India is a dual structure:\n   - **Central GST (CGST)**: Levied by the Central Government on intra-state supplies.\n   - **State GST (SGST)**: Levied by State Governments on intra-state supplies.\n   - **Integrated GST (IGST)**: Levied by the Central Government on inter-state supplies and imports.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Tax Slabs**\n   GST is levied at different rates (0%, 5%, 12%, 18%, and 28%) depending on the category of goods and services. Essential items are taxed at lower rates, while luxury and sin goods are taxed higher.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Input Tax Credit (ITC)**\n   - Businesses can claim credit for the tax paid on purchases (input tax) against the tax they collect on sales (output tax).\n   - This ensures that the final consumer bears only the GST charged by the last dealer in the supply chain.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Electronic Compliance**\n   - GST is technology-driven, with most processes handled through the **GST Network (GSTN)** portal.\n   - Businesses must file regular returns, such as GSTR-1 (outward supplies), GSTR-3B (summary return), and GSTR-9 (annual return).\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Threshold Limits**\n   - Small businesses with a turnover below \u20b940 lakh (\u20b920 lakh for special category states) are exempt from GST.\n   - Composition scheme is available for small businesses with a turnover of up to \u20b91.5 crore (\u20b975 lakh for special category states) at lower tax rates.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Inter-State Supplies**\n   IGST is levied on inter-state supplies of goods and services, and the tax revenue is shared between the Centre and the destination state.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Anti-Profiteering Measures**\n   Businesses are required to pass on the benefits of reduced tax rates and ITC to consumers by lowering prices.\n\n---\n\n### Benefits of GST:\n   - Simplified tax structure.\n   - Improved compliance and transparency.\n   - Boost to the economy by creating a unified national market.\n   - Reduction in the overall tax burden on goods and services.\n\n---\n\n### Challenges:\n   - Initial confusion and compliance burden for businesses.\n   - Frequent changes in rates and rules.\n   - Technical issues with the GSTN portal.\n\nIn summary, GST is a transformative tax reform aiming to streamline indirect taxation, reduce tax evasion, and promote economic growth in India.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
